name: N'-methyl-N'-phenylformic hydrazide
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2476
Reason: The basic unit to compare with is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. Starting from there, let's consider the functional groups present in N'-methyl-N'-phenylformic hydrazide: - We have a formyl group (C=O), which through hydrogen bonding and dipole interactions typically increases the melting point relative to benzene by about 40-50 degrees. - The hydrazide portion (NHN) introduces the possibility for hydrogen bonding and can significantly increase the melting point. Considering a similar hydrazide substituent might adjust the melting point upwards by around 50-70 degrees. - A methyl group (CH₃) attached to the nitrogen likely decreases the melting point slightly due to its electron-donating effect and reduced symmetry, perhaps by about -5 degrees. - A phenyl group (C6H5) is already considered in the base value of benzene, so we will not account for it separately here. By summing these contributions, we predict the melting point shift.
